<dl id="un6003d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un6" href="#un6003">UN6: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un6all.htm#un6003d"> (NLI.4) 3(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pimander good shepherd of men, <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un6003d"> <li>Ulysses isotext </li><li><ms href="#un6003d">MS PP-3</ms> </li><li>JJA 22:145 </li><li><a name="cd7dash" href="../udra/u3da.htm#cd7dash">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/c/cd7.htm#un6003d">Draft: 3.7</a>' </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: The Pimander (in Greek <i>&#928;&#959;&#953;&#956;&#940;&#957;&#948;&#961;&#951;&#962;</i>, Poimandres) is a work written in the second or third century AD and traditionally attributed to Hermes Trismegistus. It is a revelation account describing a vision of the creation of the universe and the nature and fate of humanity. In it, Poemandres is described as a shepherd of men. <br>Not in 1922 or 2021 texts, but in <a href="../../ulex/c/c84.htm#un6003d">1986 (3.227f)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
